The pattern you seem to be describing is activating an indexed object based on thresholds in a health value. The number of objects that you activate is directly related to the health value. Given that the maximum health is 100, you want to activate a number of objects in proportion to the remaining health.

Here's a general way to interpret the pattern in pseudo-code, considering `objects` to be an array and `health` to be the current health value:

1. Determine the total number of objects (`totalObjects`) that can be activated.
2. Calculate the threshold for activation, which would be `100 / totalObjects`.
3. Calculate the index of the object to activate based on `health` and the threshold.

Here's how you might implement this in C# for Unity, using an array of GameObjects:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class HealthBasedActivation : MonoBehaviour
{
    public GameObject[] objects; // Array of objects to activate

    // Call this method with the current health value to update object activation
    public void UpdateObjectActivation(int health)
    {
        // Make sure there's at least one object in the array
        if(objects.Length == 0) return;

        // Deactivate all objects initially
        foreach (GameObject obj in objects)
        {
            obj.SetActive(false);
        }

        // Calculate the threshold for each health segment
        int threshold = 100 / objects.Length;

        // Calculate the object index to activate based on the current health
        int objectIndex = health / threshold;

        // Decrease the index by one because array indices start at 0
        // and to activate the correct object just below the health value
        objectIndex = objectIndex - 1;

        // If health is not 100 and not a multiple of threshold, activate the next object
        if(health % threshold != 0 && health != 100) {
            objectIndex++;
        }

        // Ensure the index is within bounds of the array
        objectIndex = Mathf.Clamp(objectIndex, 0, objects.Length - 1);

        // Activate the object at the calculated index if health is not 100
        if(health != 100) {
            objects[objectIndex].SetActive(true);
        }
    }
}
```

Attach this script to a GameObject in the editor, and link your objects to the `objects` array in the inspector. Whenever the health value changes, call `UpdateObjectActivation(health)` with the new health value to activate the appropriate object.

For instance, if you have 2 objects and the health is 66, this code will activate the first object; if the health drops to 33, it will deactivate the first object and activate the second one. If you have 3 objects, it will activate the first object when health is 75, the second at health 50, and the third at health 25, respectively.

Remember to initialize the `objects` array in the Unity inspector with the GameObjects you want to activate/deactivate according to health.

